    <h2>the two wasm-pack targets</h2>
    <p>
      Both invocations live in <code>packages/sdk-rs/package.json</code> and run from
      a single Cargo manifest. The difference is the <code>--target</code> flag and
      a feature gate so the crate compiles only the bindings each runtime can use.
    </p>

    <div class="card tinted" style="padding: 18px 20px; margin: 14px 0;">
      <div class="label" style="margin-bottom: 8px;">packages/sdk-rs/package.json — wasm-pack scripts</div>
      <pre class="mono" style="margin: 0; white-space: pre-wrap; font-size: 12px; color: var(--ink-2); line-height: 1.55;">{`"build:wasm:web":  wasm-pack build --release --target web    --out-dir web-sdk-wasm  --features browser
"build:wasm:node": wasm-pack build --release --target nodejs --out-dir node-sdk-wasm --features nodejs`}</pre>
    </div>

    <p>
      The <code>web</code> target produces ES modules with <code>import.meta.url</code>-relative
      <code>.wasm</code> loading — that's what browsers and modern bundlers expect.
      The <code>nodejs</code> target produces CommonJS that loads the wasm via
      <code>fs.readFileSync</code>, which is what Node and the CLI need at startup.
      Each output gets re-packaged by a thin sibling workspace
      (<code>packages/sdk-rs/packages/web</code> and <code>.../node</code>) that
      adds <code>package.json</code>, type rollups, and (for node) a
      <code>prebuild</code> step that copies the wasm bytes into <code>src/wasm/</code>
      so <code>tsup</code> can pick them up.
    </p>

    <h2>turbo pipeline — what runs when</h2>
    <p>
      <code>turbo.json</code> declares a small pipeline. The shape that matters:
      <code>build</code> dependsOn <code>^build</code> (every workspace's deps build
      first), <code>test</code> dependsOn <code>build</code>, and <code>build:wasm</code>
      depends on a one-time <code>setup</code> task that's keyed to <code>Cargo.toml</code>
      and <code>package.json</code> so it only re-runs when toolchains shift.
    </p>

    <div class="card tinted" style="padding: 18px 20px; margin: 14px 0;">
      <div class="label" style="margin-bottom: 8px;">turbo.json — task chain</div>
      <pre class="mono" style="margin: 0; white-space: pre-wrap; font-size: 12px; color: var(--ink-2); line-height: 1.55;">{`setup       → keyed by Cargo.toml + package.json, caches .turbo/setup-cache
build:wasm  → dependsOn [setup],   outputs web-sdk-wasm/**, node-sdk-wasm/**
bundle      → dependsOn [build:wasm], outputs dist/**
build       → dependsOn [^build],  outputs dist/**, build/**, web-sdk-wasm/**
test        → dependsOn [build],   outputs coverage/**
doc         → dependsOn [build]
release     → dependsOn [build, test, lint]`}</pre>
    </div>

    <p>
      The <code>:build</code> vs <code>dev</code> story is the same shape as turbo
      everywhere: <code>build</code> writes to <code>dist/</code> with caching on,
      <code>dev</code> sets <code>cache: false</code> and <code>persistent: true</code>
      so each workspace's watcher stays alive across the workspace tree.
      <code>turbo dev --filter=./apps/web-sdk-example</code> is the practical entry
      point for a UI-led loop — turbo brings up every dependency's watcher in
      topological order and tears them all down on Ctrl-C.
    </p>

    <h2>where artifacts land</h2>
    <table style="width: 100%; font-family:'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 12px; color: var(--ink-2); border-collapse: collapse; margin: 14px 0;">
      <thead>
        <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--ink-4);">
          <th style="text-align:left; padding: 6px 0; color: var(--ink-3); font-weight: 500;">workspace</th>
          <th style="text-align:left; padding: 6px 0; color: var(--ink-3); font-weight: 500;">tool</th>
          <th style="text-align:left; padding: 6px 0; color: var(--ink-3); font-weight: 500;">output</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td style="padding: 4px 0;">packages/sdk-rs</td><td>cargo + wasm-pack</td><td>web-sdk-wasm/, node-sdk-wasm/</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 4px 0;">packages/sdk-rs/packages/web</td><td>rollup</td><td>dist/index.js + .wasm</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 4px 0;">packages/sdk-rs/packages/node</td><td>tsc + cp</td><td>dist/wasm/*.wasm, dist/wasm/index.cjs</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 4px 0;">packages/sdk-core</td><td>tsup</td><td>dist/index.{`{js,cjs,d.ts}`}</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 4px 0;">packages/sdk-services</td><td>tsup</td><td>dist/index.* + dist/{`{kv,sql}`}/</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 4px 0;">packages/web-sdk</td><td>webpack</td><td>dist/index.{`{mjs,cjs,d.ts}`}</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 4px 0;">packages/node-sdk</td><td>tsup</td><td>dist/index.* + dist/core.*</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 4px 0;">packages/cli</td><td>tsup</td><td>dist/index.js + bin/tc</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>cold install bootstrap</h2>
    <p>
      Starting from a fresh clone, the path to a buildable tree is:
    </p>
    <ol style="padding-left: 22px; margin: 6px 0 14px;">
      <li><code>bun install</code> — resolves all {totalWorkspaces} workspaces, links
        <code>workspace:*</code> deps, runs no scripts.</li>
      <li><code>bun --cwd packages/sdk-rs run setup</code> — runs <code>scripts/setup-rust.sh</code>
        once to ensure the rust toolchain + wasm-pack are present.</li>
      <li><code>bun run build</code> — turbo walks the DAG: sdk-rs wasm-pack first,
        then the two <code>*-sdk-wasm</code> packages, then sdk-core / sdk-services,
        then web-sdk / node-sdk / cli in parallel.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      <code>bun run clean</code> at the root drops every <code>dist/</code>,
      every <code>node_modules/</code>, the wasm output dirs, and the rust
      <code>target/</code> — full reset. <code>bun run demo:build</code> and
      <code>bun run node-demo</code> are <code>turbo --filter</code> shortcuts for
      bringing up just the example apps with their transitive deps.
    </p>

    <div class="card" style="padding: 18px 20px; margin: 14px 0; border-color: var(--accent);">
      <div class="label" style="margin-bottom: 6px; color: var(--accent);">why this matters for the atlas</div>
      <p style="margin: 0;">
        Every node in the DAG is also a node in the atlas. The build edges and the
        inventory edges should agree — and when they don't, that's
        <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/09/`}>chapter 09</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>data this chapter reads</h3>
    <ul class="col gap-4">
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/inventory.json</li>
      <li class="mono">package.json (root) — workspaces, scripts</li>
      <li class="mono">turbo.json — task pipeline</li>
      <li class="mono">packages/sdk-rs/package.json — wasm-pack invocations</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>where to read next</h3>
    <p>
      Chapter <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/09/`}>09</a> closes the loop —
      how the atlas detects when its own picture of this DAG has drifted from
      reality, and what an engineer does when it has.
    </p>
  </article>
</Atlas>
